Datasets.
We experiment on 666 graph benchmark datasets from various domains (Sen et al., 2008; Pei et al., 2020; Tang et al., 2009), including Cora, dRisk, Actor, Corn, Texas, and Wisconsin.
Table 1 presents the statistics of these datasets, including the numbers of nodes, edges, and node attributes.

Main results.
We benchmark all the methods across 666 real-world datasets.
In Table 2, we observe that CCVGAE (ours) can reliably compete others with up to 29%percent2929\% improvement regarding AUC and 19%percent1919\% improvement regarding AP.
Recall that CCVGAE improves on VGAE by integrating a causal layer to encourage disentangled representations, suggesting that the significant improvement is due to the expressiveness of those disentangled representations.
SIG-VAE improve the representation by imposing graph structure-aware distributions instead of independent Gaussian, which results in better performance than VGAE.
DGAE enhances VGAE by deepening GCN layers resulting in a better result than VGAE, especially for non-Euclidean data.

Module Importance. Recall that, for representation learning, we employ a causal structure to enforce disentanglement, which is DAG-structured ΦΦ\Phi in Eq. 5.
Thereby, we investigate how our method performs without such a causality structure constraint, called CCVGAE w/o CC.
In Table 2, we find that the model without the DAG constraint , i.e., CCVGAE w/o CC, reduces the absolute performance by 12%percent1212\% and 12%percent1212\% regarding AUC and AP, respectively.
These ablation results suggest the necessity of causal structure in our model.

Main results.
In Table 3, we present the performance of all methods under different settings.
Our method, CC-Meta-Graph, outperforms others consistently, providing up to a 11%percent1111\% absolute improvement.
Notably, we can see that with 5%percent55\% of the data, the performance of CC-Meta-Graph is competitive with the others given 10%percent1010\%, suggesting that our model can produce better generalizable representations with much less data and align with the consistency property.
